at I\'ve read:\n- `Flow.kill()` sets `error`, `intercepted = False`, `live = Fal
se`, and sets `_resume_event` if present\n- `MessageInjected` is generic because
messages have different payload types\n- `inject_event` routes by `client_conn.i
d` (or peername/sockname for UDP)\n- Per-protocol subclasses of `MessageInjected
` exist: `TcpMessageInjected`, `UdpMessageInjected`, `WebSocketMessageInjected`\
n- The HTTP layer handles `MessageInjected` by routing to the appropriate stream
\n\nFor issue #5484, it seems to be about killing intercepted flows not working.
