ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Now I have a good understanding of the architecture. Let me think thr
ough the four questions:\n\n**Q1: Per-protocol vs single generic `KillInjected`?
**\n\n`MessageInjected` is generic because messages have different payload types
. `KillInjected` has no payload. \n\nArguments for A (per-protocol):\n- Pattern 
match with existing code\n- `@expect` decorators can reference specific types\n-
But: there\'s no `HttpMessageInjected` today! The HTTP layer handles `MessageInj
ected` directly in `HttpLayer._handle_event`, routing to streams. It doesn\'t ha
ve a per-protocol subclass. So the pattern is ALREADY broken for HTTP.\n- For TC
P/UDP/WebSocket, they have per-protocol subclasses because they parameterize on 
message type.\n\nArguments for B (single generic):\n- Cleaner, less boilerplate\
n- No payload-type reason to split\n- The HTTP layer already handles `MessageInj
ected` generically\n- `inject_event` is typed to take `events.MessageInjected` (
the base class), so it already works with the base type\n\nActually wait, lookin
g at `inject_event`:\n```python\ndef inject_event(self, event: events.MessageInj
ected):\n```\n\nIt\'s typed to take the base class `MessageInjected`! And in `Ht
tpLayer._handle_event`:\n```python\nelif isinstance(event, events.MessageInjecte
d):\n```\n\nThis handles the base class. So the architecture ALREADY uses the ba
se class for routing in some places.\n\nFor `KillInjected`, since there\'s no pa
yload, Option B (single generic) seems much more natural. The `@expect` decorato
rs would all reference `KillInjected`, which is fine. The only reason to use per
-protocol subclasses would be if different layers needed to handle them differen
tly... but they all do the same thing: close connections and mark the flow as ki
lled.\n\nHowever, there\'s a subtle point: `TcpMessageInjected`, `UdpMessageInje
cted`, `WebSocketMessageInjected` exist not just for payload typing but also so 
that layers can use `@expect(..., TcpMessageInjected)` — the `@expect` decorator
checks `isinstance(event, event_types)`. If we use a single `KillInjected`, all 
layers just add `KillInjected` to their `@expect` tuple. That\'s simpler.\n\nBut
wait, the HTTP layer\'s `HttpStream` doesn\'t use `@expect` for `MessageInjected
` — it checks in `HttpLayer._handle_event` and routes to the stream. For `KillIn
jected`, we\'d need the same approach: `HttpLayer` catches it and routes to the 
right `HttpStream`.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, `HttpStream
` is a `layer.Layer` subclass. It has `_handle_event` and states. But `HttpLayer
` intercepts `MessageInjected` before it reaches `HttpStream`. For `KillInjected
`, we\'d want similar behavior.\n\nIf we use Option B (single `KillInjected`), t
he flow is:\n1. `inject_event` sends `KillInjected` to the connection handler\n2
. The top layer (maybe `HttpLayer`, `TcpLayer`, `UdpLayer`, etc.) receives it\n3
. Each layer handles it appropriately\n\nFor `HttpLayer`, it would catch `KillIn
jected` and route to the right stream, similar to `MessageInjected`.\nFor `TcpLa
yer`/`UdpLayer`/`WebSocketLayer`, they\'d catch it in their `@expect` decorators
.\n\nThis seems clean. Option A adds boilerplate with no real benefit. The maint
ainer (Maximilian Hils) seems like someone who values clean, minimal abstraction
s. I\'d pick **B**.\n\n**Q2: Where is the event emitted?**\n\nOption A: `Flow.ki
ll()` emits the event. But `Flow` is a data class in `mitmproxy/flow.py` and doe
sn\'t import proxy events. This would couple it to the proxy infrastructure.\n\n
Option B: `core.py:flow.kill` command calls `f.kill()` then asks proxyserver to 
inject. This is similar to how message injection works — the addon commands (`in
ject.tcp`, etc.) create the event and call `inject_event`.\n\nOption C: New `inj
ect.kill` command. Most exact mirror of `inject.tcp`/`inject.udp`/`inject.websoc
ket`.\n\nLooking at the call sites:\n1. `core.py:92` — `flow.kill` command\n2. `
view.py:435` — `view.flows.remove` calls `f.kill()` if killable\n3. `view.py:598
` — `view.kill` hook just updates the view\n\nIf we put emission in `Flow.kill()
`, then ALL call sites automatically emit. But it breaks layering.\n\nIf we put 
it in `core.py:flow.kill`, then `view.py:435` won\'t emit the event. The `view.f
lows.remove` command would need to also emit.\n\nOption C (`inject.kill`) is int
eresting. The current `inject.tcp`/`inject.udp`/`inject.websocket` commands are 
protocol-specific because they need to validate the flow type and create protoco
l-specific messages. For `KillInjected`, since we\'d use a single generic event 
(Q1=B), `inject.kill` would just take any `Flow` and emit `KillInjected`.\n\nBut
wait, the `core.py:flow.kill` command is the user-facing "kill flows" command. T
he `inject.*` commands are separate. If we add `inject.kill`, we\'d need to chan
ge `core.py:flow.kill` to call `inject.kill` (or both `f.kill()` and `inject.kil
l`).\n\nLooking at the pattern for `MessageInjected`:\n- The addon-facing API is
`inject.tcp`/`inject.udp`/`inject.websocket` \n- These create the event and call
`inject_event`\n- `Flow.kill()` is a pure state mutation\n- The `flow.kill` comm
and is a UI command that calls `f.kill()`\n\nIf we make `Flow.kill()` emit, we c
ouple the data model to the proxy. That\'s bad.\n\nIf we put emission in `core.p
y:flow.kill`, we only catch one call site. `view.py:remove` also calls `f.kill()
`. We\'d need to update both.\n\nIf we add `inject.kill`, we get a clean separat
ion: `inject.kill` is the proxy event emitter, and `flow.kill` is the UI command
that calls both `f.kill()` and `inject.kill`. But then `view.py:remove` would al
so need to call `inject.kill`.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at `view.py:4
35`:\n```python\nif f.killable:\n    f.kill()\n```\n\nThis is in `view.flows.rem
ove`. If you remove a flow from the view while it\'s live, it kills it. This sho
uld also emit the event.\n\nThe cleanest approach might be to have `Flow.kill()`
emit, but abstract the emission so `flow.py` doesn\'t directly depend on proxy e
vents. For example, `Flow.kill()` could call a hook/callback that the proxy serv
er registers.\n\nBut wait, `Flow` already has `ctx` stuff? No, looking at `flow.
py`, it doesn\'t import `ctx`. It\'s a pure data class (well, `serializable.Seri
alizable`).\n\nOption B (emission from `core.py:flow.kill`) doesn\'t cover `view
.py:remove`.\nOption C (`inject.kill`) could be called from both `core.py:flow.k
ill` and `view.py:remove`.\n\nActually, looking at the architecture, the most co
nsistent approach with `MessageInjected` is:\n1. Keep `Flow.kill()` as a pure st
ate mutation\n2. Add `inject.kill` command in `proxyserver.py` \n3. Update `core
.py:flow.kill` to call both `f.kill()` and `inject.kill`\n4. Update `view.py:rem
ove` to call both `f.kill()` and `inject.kill`\n\nBut that means duplicating the
`inject.kill` call in multiple places. Alternatively, we could make `Flow.kill()
` trigger the event emission via some indirection.\n\nWait, let me re-read the T
ODO:\n> "An alternative approach would be to introduce a `KillInjected` event si
milar to `MessageInjected`, which should fix this issue."\n\nThe maintainer\'s T
ODO is IN `Flow.kill()`. This suggests the maintainer was thinking about doing t
his work in or near `Flow.kill()`. But as a TODO comment, it\'s just a note.\n\n
I think the cleanest approach is Option B with a twist: make `Flow.kill()` stay 
pure, but centralize the event emission in the addon commands. But since there a
re multiple call sites, maybe we should look at whether `view.py:remove` should 
even be calling `f.kill()` or if it should call the `flow.kill` command.\n\nActu
ally, `view.py:remove` is an addon command. It could call `ctx.master.commands.c
all("flow.kill", [f])` or just emit the event directly.\n\nLet me think about wh
at the maintainer would prefer. The `MessageInjected` pattern is:\n- `inject_eve
